CAN2 can not transmit on PB_13. All other variations are OK, both with CAN1 and with CAN2. Checked on a real CAN bus with logic analyzer.

### Description
- Type: Bug
- Priority: Minor

---------------------------------------------------------------
## Bug

**Target**
STM32F429ZI (Discovery board)

**Toolchain:**
GCC_ARM|ARM (EmBitz, Online compiler)

**Expected behavior**
Successful transmission on PB_13.

**Actual behavior**
CAN2 can not transmit on PB_13.

**Steps to reproduce**
Try to transmit a CAN frame with CAN interface 2 on PB_13 as CAN TD pin. See example code below.

```
#include "mbed.h" //5.4.7 (144)

const PinName can1rxPins[] = {PB_8, PD_0, PA_11};
const PinName can1txPins[] = {PB_9, PD_1, PA_12};
const PinName can2rxPins[] = {PB_12, PB_5};
const PinName can2txPins[] = {PB_13, PB_6};

//CAN1
//0,0=OK 0,1=OK 0,2=OK 1,0=OK 1,1=OK 1,2=OK 2,0=OK 2,1=OK 2,2=OK
//CAN2
//0,0=RX_OK 0,1=OK 1,0=RX_OK 1,1=OK

//CAN can(can1rxPins[0], can1txPins[0]);
CAN can(can2rxPins[0], can2txPins[0]);

Serial serialDebug(PA_9, PA_10);  //UART1, Tx, Rx (Debug)
DigitalOut led1(LED1);
DigitalOut led2(LED2);

Thread sendThread(osPriorityAboveNormal, 2048);

CANMessage messageIn;
CANMessage messageOut;

void canRxIsr()
{
    can.read(messageIn);
    led1 = !led1;
}

void sendMessage()
{
    int status = can.write(messageOut);
    serialDebug.printf("Send status: %d\r\n", status);
}

void sendMessageLoop()
{
    while (true)
    {
        sendMessage();
        osDelay(1000);
    }
}

int main()
{
    serialDebug.baud(460800);
    serialDebug.printf("CAN receive / transmit test.\r\n");
    can.frequency(125000);

    messageOut.id = 0xD70000E;
    messageOut.format = CANExtended;
    messageOut.len = 0;

    can.attach(&canRxIsr);
    sendThread.start(&sendMessageLoop);

    while (true)
    {
        led2 = !led2;
        led1 = 0;
        osDelay(1000);
    }
}
```

### Description
- Type: Bug
- Priority: Major

---------------------------------------------------------------
## Bug

**Target**
XDOT_L151CC

**Toolchain:**
GCC_ARM|ARM
Did not test IAR but is likely an issue with that toolchain as well.

**Toolchain version:**
arm-none-eabi-gcc (GNU Tools for ARM Embedded Processors) 4.9.3 20150529 (release) [ARM/embedded-4_9-branch revision 227977]
uVision V5.21.1.0

**mbed-cli version:** 
0.9.1

**meed-os sha:**
fc18365 Merge pull request #4463 from ARMmbed/release-candidate (mbed-os-5.4.7)

**DAPLink version:**
0241

**Expected behavior**
After waking from a low power mode, the us tick should function just like it did before entering a low power mode.

**Actual behavior**
The prescaler for TIM5 (the mbed us tick) has changed from 31 to 9, causing issues with Timers, Tickers, etc.

**Steps to reproduce**
The following application reproduces with mbed-os-5.4.7.

```c++
#include "mbed.h"
#include "hal_tick.h"
#include "mbed_rtx.h"

Serial pc(USBTX, NC);

void countdown(int count) {
    DigitalOut led(LED1);
    Timer timer;
    timer.start();

    while ( count-- > 0 ) {
        printf("Count %d: %d msec\r\n", count, timer.read_ms());
        led = 1; wait_ms(150);
        led = 0; wait_ms(850);
    }
}

void fix_tick() {
    if ( TIM_MST->PSC != OS_CLOCK / 1000000 - 1 ) {
        TIM_MST->PSC = OS_CLOCK / 1000000 - 1;
        TIM_MST->EGR = TIM_EVENTSOURCE_UPDATE;
        while ( TIM_MST->EGR & ~TIM_EVENTSOURCE_UPDATE ) {};
    }
}

int main() {
    pc.baud(115200);

    countdown(5);

    hal_deepsleep();
    //fix_tick();

    countdown(5);
}
```

Without the tick prescaler getting fixed, output will demonstrate that the tick has been broken.

> Count 4: 0 msec
> Count 3: 1001 msec
> Count 2: 2003 msec
> Count 1: 3004 msec
> Count 0: 4006 msec
> Count 4: 0 msec
> Count 3: 3202 msec
> Count 2: 6406 msec
> Count 1: 9609 msec
> Count 0: 12812 msec

If the tick prescaler is fixed using the fix_tick function, output will be as expected.

> Count 4: 0 msec                                                    
> Count 3: 1001 msec                                                 
> Count 2: 2003 msec                                                 
> Count 1: 3004 msec
> Count 0: 4006 msec
> Count 4: 0 msec
> Count 3: 1001 msec
> Count 2: 2003 msec
> Count 1: 3004 msec
> Count 0: 4006 msec
